<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / S Africa parties seek votes deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK SUZMAN, MICHAEL HOLMAN and PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
South Africa's main political parties were negotiating a share-out of
disputed votes yesterday from the country's first all-race elections, after
the Independent Electoral Commission in effect abandoned a conventional
tally for political expediency.
IEC officials said privately that a deal had been struck at regional level
between the African National Congress and the rival Inkatha Freedom party in
Natal, the most heavily disputed province, to ensure that Inkatha emerges as
the largest party there. But the leadership of the ANC, the second largest
party in Natal and overall winner of the general election, had yet to
endorse the agreement.
The moves came as electoral officials early today ended a temporary halt to
the release of results, announcing that the ANC had won 64.9 per cent of the
votes with 15m counted out of the total of 23m. This brought the party close
to the 66 per cent threshold which would allow it unilaterally to change the
constitution.
The IEC, charged under the law with conducting elections and pronouncing on
their integrity, made clear it would endorse any agreement reached among
political parties, irrespective of voting totals.
Mr Justice Johann Kriegler, the embattled IEC chairman, said the commission
'would certainly not stand in the way' of parties resolving disputes among
themselves.
Asked whether the IEC ought not to judge disputes independently in
determining whether to endorse the elections, Judge Kriegler replied: 'If
the objector and the objectee come to terms, that is universally accepted as
legitimate in the political game . . . Let's not get overly squeamish.'
Judge Kriegler said he believed the presidential inauguration could take
place on schedule next Tuesday.
ANC farm policy, Page 4
Science sans sanctions, Page 21
Lord Callaghan, Page 25
</TEXT>
