<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / The Lex Column: Lufthansa
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Lufthansa's deal with the German government over how future pension
liabilities are to be split has paved the way for a decisive break with its
public sector past. The airline's culture has changed over the past two
years as top management has realised that a low cost base is essential in an
increasingly competitive industry. But Lufthansa's profile in international
capital markets has inevitably been affected by the government's majority
stake - something which could not change so long as the pension issue was
unresolved.
Now, though, Bonn is free to sell its stake, while the airline can press
ahead with its own rights issue. This comes at a good time, as Lufthansa's
profit and loss account is being transformed by the twin effects of strong
recovery in demand and vigorous cost-cutting. The group is expected to move
marginally into profit in the current year and strongly thereafter.
Some of this story is already incorporated in the share price, which has
outperformed the DAX index by more than 50 per cent in the past year. But
there is room for more. Using the yardstick of market capitalisation to
turnover, Lufthansa does not look expensive. Its ratio of 35 per cent is
similar to KLM's but less than half that of British Airways. BA, of course,
deserves a higher rating because its structural changes are much further
advanced than those of its continental rivals. But the wide gap in the
ratings shows the possible upside in Lufthansa's share price if it can catch
up.
</TEXT>
