<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Nostalgia for communist comfort: Passionate divisions behind
Sunday's Hungarian election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON and EDWARD MORTIMER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For the outside world, it is clear enough what Hungary's election is about.
It will either reverse or, more probably, confirm the pattern of former
communists returning to power through the ballot-box, which now affects
almost all of central and eastern Europe.
The reason for this swing of the pendulum is no secret. While the scope of
reforms varies, the collapse of the communist system has brought social and
economic dislocation, unemployment, widening income differentials and, at
least initially, steeply falling output. Even in a country like Poland,
where gross domestic product began to grow again last year, unemployment
continued to rise.
Everywhere (except Russia) the former communists have changed their name.
All claim to be converted to the virtues of the free market, with a large
private sector, as well as multi-party democracy. But everywhere they have
benefited from public disillusionment with the first fruits of capitalism,
and have encouraged people to think that, with them in charge, the
transition can be managed more gently, with better protection for those who
stand to lose.
Yet when it comes to specific policies, their room for manoeuvre is small.
In Poland the ex-communists, now in government, find themselves struggling
to hold down wages and contain public expenditure, against the populist
demands of the Solidarity trade union. And in Hungary, while their attacks
on the conservative government's economic record and their claims that the
country is on the verge of economic disintegration have contributed to their
commanding lead in opinion polls, the Socialists (formerly communists) do
not offer any sharp change of policy.
In fact, economic policy as such has been almost absent from the Hungarian
election campaign. Every party agrees that income tax rates need to be
brought down, but none has staked out a position as the party of tax cuts.
All the main parties proclaim their belief in privatisation, and in economic
integration with western Europe.
Even where there are differences, they tend to be within political blocs
rather than between them. The fiercest criticisms of the government's
privatisation policy have come from the right wing of the ruling party, the
Hungarian Democratic Forum (MDF), and from its Christian Democrat coalition
partners. And the government presents its economic achievements, such as
more than Dollars 7bn in foreign investment, as fruits of gradualism rather
than 'shock therapy'.
The opposition Free Democrats - generally seen as to the left of the MDF,
and now as potential coalition partners of the Socialists - are, in fact, to
the right on economic policy issues: 'revolutionaries posing as yuppies', in
the bon mot of one of their founders, they favour more economic freedom,
less state control or intervention. Their fellow-liberals in the Federation
of Young Democrats ('Fidesz') are regarded as further to the right -
'yuppies posing as revolutionaries'  - because they are more firmly hostile
to the Socialists. Yet one of the Fidesz leaders, Jozsef Szajer, told the FT
recently that 'free market rhetoric wouldn't work in Hungary: no one here
believes in a simple, idealistic structure of any kind'. He went on to argue
for a consensual economic policy based on agreement between government,
unions and employers.
The Socialist party itself has the high priest of fiscal restraint in the
shape of Laszlo Bekesi, a former and perhaps future finance minister,
alongside a trade union wing that promises higher social spending and
government action to save troubled industries. (The party leader, Gyula
Horn, has good reformist credentials as the foreign minister who tore down
the barbed wire between Hungary and Austria in 1989, but also a more dubious
past as a militiaman in the grim period after the 1956 revolution.)
In short, economic policy is not what divides the parties. Voters' feelings
about the economy may be the decisive factor in the election, but the
political class reserves its passion for 'the national question'.
This is, in essence, a question about what makes a Hungarian: ethnicity or
citizenship? The late Jozsef Antall, founder of the MDF and prime minister
until his death last December, once said he considered himself the prime
minister in spirit of 15m Hungarians. Hungary has only 10m inhabitants, but
Antall's concept of the nation included Hungarian-speakers in neighbouring
countries. Left-wingers, both liberal and socialist, regard such talk as
dangerous, potentially even for the Hungarian minorities themselves, since
it tends to increase suspicion of them among their fellow-citizens.
Intellectuals maintain that there is a deep and unbridgeable divide in
Hungarian society between liberals and conservatives. Socialists, even after
half a century of communist rule, are regarded as a sub-category within the
liberal camp.
Perhaps it is not surprising that this should be the view of a rightwing
intellectual like Istvan Csurka, the nationalist playwright who split from
the MDF two years ago to form his own splinter group, the Hungarian Truth
and Life Party. What is surprising is that many liberals see politics in
rather similar terms. This is particularly true of the Free Democrats,
despite their origins in the anti-communist opposition of the 1980s. Many of
their original leaders were the offspring of committed communists, and many
had begun their careers as Marxist dissidents before graduating to
liberalism. Many, including perhaps half the top leadership of the party,
are also Jewish.
The readiness of right-wing nationalist leaders like Csurka to resort to
anti-semitism is thus not entirely surprising; and the Free Democrats made a
sort of concession to it when they picked Gabor Kuncze, a previously little
known provincial politician, as their candidate for prime minister. Election
posters featuring their previous leader, Ivan Peto, who comes from a Jewish
and communist family, are frequently spray-painted with the star of David.
Kuncze is a Christian, whose mustachioed features give him an 'authentic
Hungarian' look (to borrow Csurka's terminology).
Csurka has happily been marginalised. But many liberals argue that the
mainstream MDF retains the instincts of a Catholic, authoritarian,
nationalist party. Even Gaspar Miklos Tamas, a Free Democrat MP who once
described himself as a 'central European Tory', now grudgingly admits that
he would regard a Socialist victory as a lesser evil than a continuation of
the present government. 'One may have doubts about the genuineness of the
Socialists' conversion to democracy,' he says, 'but these people (the MDF)
positively hate it.' As proof of this somewhat extreme proposition he cites
the sacking or forced retirement of 129 journalists from the state-owned
radio last February, which prompted large demonstrations both for and
against.
Feelings run equally high on the other side. An adviser to the present prime
minister, Peter Boross, accuses the Free Democrats of advising western
countries to withhold credits from the present government, and makes a
seemingly far-fetched link between such 'unpatriotic' behaviour and the
shortlived bolshevik dictatorship of Bela Kun, which followed Hungary's
defeat in the first world war.
Only the Young Democrats have tried to rise above this apparently
anachronistic kulturkampf, but it is far from clear they have succeeded. A
year ago they were riding high in opinion polls and tipped by some as
leaders of the next government. But their efforts to reassure provincial
conservative voters by calling themselves 'national liberals' - stressing
their concern for Hungarian minorities abroad, repudiating any anti-clerical
tendencies and hinting that they would prefer a coalition with the MDF to
one with the Socialists - provoked a split in the party and hostile press
comment.
Today, Fidesz leaders claim their first preference would still be a liberal
government, formed by themselves and the Free Democrats. But no one
seriously expects an election result that would make this possible.
Hungarians are being asked to choose between left and right, not in the
sense of socialism versus capitalism, but in the much older sense of
'cosmopolitan' free-thinkers versus Christian nationalists. In 1990 an
anti-communist backlash brought victory to the right. This time, nostalgia
for the relative comfort of 'goulash communism' seems likely to favour the
left.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>HUZ  Hungary, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
