<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Observer: Building talk
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The latest upheaval in the building society movement - the proposed merger
of the Northern Rock and the North of England, raises a question. Can there
be some curious connection between glossy new headquarters and society
mergers?
The North of England is soon to move from the centre of Sunderland to a new
HQ on the edge of Sunderland, at the Doxford business park. Similarly the
Universal, one of the smaller societies, in merger talks with the Tynemouth,
recently moved to smart new premises in central Newcastle. The Leeds, in
swank new premises, was in merger discussions, abandoned last autumn, with
the National &amp; Provincial, and the Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester, soon to be
digested by Lloyds Bank, hasn't long been in its glitzy premises on the
outskirts of Gloucester.
So where does this leave the Newcastle Building Society which is planning to
move into its imposing Pounds 10m HQ in the centre of Newcastle? A prime
target for the Northern Rock's expansion minded management team?
Not so, says Newcastle chief executive Bill Midgley, who likens the
phenomenon to football teams building new stands, only to be relegated the
following season. 'We have to concentrate our minds on making the profits to
pay for our new headquarters.'
Fighting talk, Bill.
</TEXT>
