<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Observer: Right stuff
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
In Brazil, plagued by near hyperinflation and bad governments for more than
a decade, success stories like Ayrton Senna don't come round too often.
Hence the death of the Formula One racing driver almost brought Latin
America's biggest country to a halt yesterday, when his coffin was paraded
through the street of Sao Paulo, atop a fire engine.
President Itamar Franco had already declared three days of mourning and
delayed the announcement of a new currency until next week, while Rubens
Ricupero, Brazil's new finance minister, compares Senna's death to the loss
of the US space shuttle Challenger.
'For a country which has still not sent people into space, Senna was the
hero in the vanguard of technology and proof of our ability to win among the
most modern and new. Senna was our astronaut,' says Ricupero.
</TEXT>
