<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Letters to the Editor: Fine not an appropriate response
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr CRAIG GILLESPIE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Can anybody tell me what purpose is served by imposing a fine on a
mutual society such as Norwich Union? As I understand it, the Financial
Services Act was introduced to help protect the public from financial loss
through being sold inappropriate long-term financial products. Mutual
societies have no shareholders, so all their profits are distributed to
their with-profits policyholders. Therefore, those who suffer financial loss
from the imposition of a fine are the very people the legislation was
designed to protect.
Surely more thought could be given to the penalties imposed for
infringements of the regulators' rules? For instance, fines could be imposed
on directors and chief executives or regulators could be given the power to
remove the chief executive of a persistent offender.
Craig Gillespie,
42 Stoats Nest Village,
Coulsdon, Surrey
</TEXT>
