<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Politics is big on the airwaves tonight. The BBC has a comprehensive
coverage of today's UK local government elections at 11.30pm, and Channel 4
(9pm) looks at Russia's first free parliamentary election last year in
Moscow Central, part of the Bite the Ballot series.
Producer Clive Gordon won a 1993 BAFTA for his investigation of Bosnia, but
this time he goes for the bizarre. He focuses on three candidates competing
to represent Moscow: one has to prove his sanity to be declared a candidate;
another is reckoned to be a local mobster; and a third, an exiled
millionaire, can only return to Russia because he is standing for
parliament.
With crime such a hot issue, the vigilante is becoming a popular hero. In
Taking Liberties (BBC 2, 8pm), Polly Toynbee asks whether juries are too
lenient in cases in which citizens take matters into their own hands so
enthusiastically that innocent people die as a consequence.
At last, the cricket team in Outside Edge (ITV, 8.30pm) gets to play a
match. Richard Harris' play has been running out of steam of late but this
should be a happy climax.
</TEXT>
