<DATE>940505
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Arts: In the spirit of myth-making - Cinema
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INNOCENT MOVES (PG) Steven Zaillian
THE PAPER (15) Ron Howard
WHAT'S EATING GILBERT GRAPE? (12) Lasse Hallstrom
MY FATHER THE HERO (PG) Steve Miner
We all know why we love Hollywood, when we do not bow to intellectual dogma
and say we hate it: because the place is determined to turn the mundane into
the magical. Look at Innocent Moves, a film about a father-child
relationship tested by the boy's rise as a chess prodigy. And even when the
transformation does not quite work - listen for the sound of creaking
corsetry and snapping stays as The Paper inflates the journalist's life into
a melodrama the size of Mr Blobby - we love Hollywood for its urge to risk
all in pursuit of the grand and passionate.
I have just come back from the place and can testify that nothing has
changed. Little can dent Tinseltowners' up-and-at-em nature: not
earthquakes, nor murders, nor smog, nor the worst post-Oscars famine of good
American movies I can remember. Topping the box office was - ultimate
humiliation for non-limeys - a British film: the romantic comedy Four
Weddings And A Funeral, opening here next week.
So what has happened to the men and women lost in self-congratulation only a
month ago, when Schindler's List swept a quality Oscars night? Looking for
fresh directions and fresh directors - while staying true to the myth-making
spirit. One Oscar winner, Schindler screenwriter Steven Zaillian, has got
behind a camera and made Innocent Moves: a film so good that it did only
medium business in the US under the over-enterprising name Searching For
Bobby Fischer. This title recklessly assumed familiarity with Fischer's name
in a country where many people have not heard of Arthur Miller, Einstein or
the Pope.
The plot is plain. Seven-year-old Josh, played by real-life chess prodigy
Max Pomeranc, rises from early promise outwitting chess hustlers in New
York's Washington Square to a will-he-won't-he finale in which he faces the
reigning champ. But the drama is less in the climax than in all that goes
before. Zaillian moves the characters themselves around like thinking chess
pieces. Joe Mantegna is kindly-bullying Dad, charging forward or sideways
like a chutzpah-fortified castle. Ben Kingsley is Josh's European teacher,
zigzagging in crafty knight moves. And imperious Robert Stephens, the
rival's mentor, drawls in bishop-like diagonals across every crowded room.
Some Copland-ish music by James Horner reminds us how close this film could
have been to pure American corn. But intelligence keeps outflanking mere
inspirationalism. Zaillian knows when to hasten his story with montage
sequences, pasting-and-scissoring whole weeks or months in speedy scrapbooks
of images. And he knows when to slow to one perfect, glowing image: like the
close-ups of Pomeranc (excellent), sitting luminous in thought over his
chequered battleground.
Newspaper buildings, as we all know who work in them, are orderly places
full of crisp business suits and calm, incisive decision-making. But what is
a newspaper office in a Hollywood movie? To judge by The Paper - idiotically
enjoyable even when idiotic - it is something between the bridge of the
Titanic and the last days of Pompeii.
Michael Keaton, city editor of the New York Sun, needs a crisis a day to
keep his adrenalin going. So writers David and Stephen Koepp and director
Ron Howard (Backdraft, Far And Away) decide to test him with an overdose.
What about three crises? In the morning and evening our baby-faced perpetuum
mobile must deal with a miscarried justice story about two young blacks
wrongly arrested for a shooting. In the afternoon he has a job interview at
the snooty New York Sentinel (read New York Times). And throughout the day
his wife Marisa Tomei is in the last stages of pregnancy.
This New York could exist only in Hollywood. But the advantage of
over-egging a pudding is that no one can complain about the quality of the
eggs. Dome-pated Robert Duvall sizzles away as Keaton's editor, whose own
panjandrum of crises includes an estranged daughter and a 'prostate the size
of a bagel.' There is Randy Quaid, hardboiled hack par excellence. And there
is the toughest egg of all, assistant editor Glenn Close. She insists on
'rolling the presses' - cue trembling floorboards and San Andreas sound
effects in the upstairs newsroom - before Keaton has made his final dash to
the cop shop for that clinching piece of police evidence for his 'They
didn't do it' story.
Add a fight and another shooting and by the last reel almost everyone is
being carried off in an ambulance. But in Hollywood this is what they think
of as real life. No day goes by there without the sweet music of
emergency-service sirens. The Paper has nothing to do with the New York
newspaper business, everything to do with the nerves of a city where a day
without make-or-break news is counted a day lost.
The whimsical, under-energised What's Eating Gilbert Grape? demonstrates
another truth about America's movie capital. Hollywoodites believe that once
you step outside Los Angeles time stands still. The entire country - this
film is set in Endora, Iowa - consists of hicks, hillbillies and the
handicapped, frozen in American Gothic postures. Strike that frown: clasp
that pitchfork: chew, if possible, that cornstalk.
Here is stalk-chewing Johnny Depp, who divides his days between tending his
oversize Momma - 'Did yer ever see a beached whale on television?' is how he
describes her to strangers - and saving his mentally retarded brother
Leonardo DiCaprio from suicidal escapades. DiCaprio keeps climbing the town
water tower, to the distress of Depp and the enthusiastic curiosity of
undertaker Crispin Glover. Then a girl floats into town. She is Juliette
Lewis, a trailer waif with a line in mystical repartee. Show her a sky and
she will quaver 'So-o limitless]' Which boy, if either, will she enchant or
ensnare? Screenwriter Peter Hedges, adapting his own novel, must have been
force-fed Carson McCullers as a child. Archness and bucolic surrealism
reign, though McCullers herself would have ensured there was some muscle
under the mimsy mythopoeia.
But better Gilbert Grape than My Father The Hero. This time Hollywood takes
an even larger step outside its own borders and an even smaller step
imaginatively. Remake a recent French movie. Hire the same star, Gerard
Depardieu, to play the jealous father holidaying with his nubile daughter on
a paradise isle. Have the daughter pretend that Dad is her ageing boyfriend.
And then sit back to watch the film nosedive at the box office. Deservedly
too. For the original film's slender wit and charm, read the Disney Studio
stomping across the sand in size-12 schmaltz-boots.
Hollywood could not, of course, get to the all-French-made Germinal, also
starring Depardieu. But unfortunately neither could I. I returned from
Lotusland on Sunday to find that the press show, like that for M. Butterfly,
had happened last week. Watch for both in next week's space.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
