<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Technology: All fingers and thumbs - The search for a
machine that reads prints
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY and ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A tussle is going on in the UK government over the politically sensitive
issue of whether to bring in identity cards to tackle social security fraud.
On one side is the Department of Social Security, which opposes such a move
for the millions of social security claimants. On the other is the
government's efficiency unit, which has just gained the support of the
Treasury for its view in favour of identity cards.
The Treasury's influence could be decisive in paving the way for the issue
of cards. But whoever wins the argument, the search will go on for a
foolproof biometric system of data access and cash and benefits
dispensation. This is a system where a single body measurement, say a
fingerprint, will suffice to identify a claimant and so authorise a payment.
Thorn Secure Systems, part of Thorn-EMI of the UK, and Electronic Data
Systems, the information technology subsidiary of General Motors of the US,
are thought to be the frontrunners for welfare identity cards in Britain.
They and others are believed to have offered various systems, including
watermarks, handscans and fingerprints. All, however, would be linked to
cards in some way - either swipe cards or smart cards.
The problems with fingerprints are threefold: no one applies the same
pressure twice; the angle of approach is always different; and scratches,
cuts and scar tissue contaminate the print.
This leads to an unacceptable level of false rejections and false
acceptances. False acceptances can mean fraud; while false rejections can
mean frustration - with a machine denying that you are who you say you are.
The only fingerprint recognition system in operation over the past year is
in Los Angeles County, for the welfare department's general relief scheme.
Recently, it was extended to cover aid to families with dependent children.
Well over 100,000 families are involved.
Lisa Nunnez, the welfare department's head of computer services, claims the
system, from software consultancy EDS, will save the county tens of millions
of dollars each year. But she agrees that it is only 95 per cent effective,
even though prints are taken from two fingers.
This level of failure is probably too high for the UK, where there is a
great aversion to identification cards of any kind. Cards linked to
fingerprinting are a particular anathema, conjuring up images of criminal
activity and a police state.
Now, however, Harry Takhar of Jasper Consulting in Bemidji, Minnesota has
made an extraordinary claim for a fingerprint biometric system, which may
have cut the mistakes to an acceptable level.
The problem is speed. To be useful in the real world, recognition must take
only fractions of a second. Human fingerprint experts are adept at matching
'cold' prints with samples held in a fingerprint library, but they take
minutes if not hours to complete a match. Computers are fast but cannot
approach human pattern-recognition abilities.
Takhar is enthusiastic about the way his system solves the problem. Prints
are scanned raster-fashion, the way a television picture is built up, and
the result processed to present a clean image. Elements of the print -
distance from the core to the periphery, the numbers of whorls and arches
and so on - are then calculated.
Takhar describes this in terms of a child's join-the-dots picture. The
fingerprint image represents the completed picture, the calculations place
the dots in the picture. It is then possible to calculate a unique number
from the position of the dots. Combined with other information - a social
security number, for example - a 64-element number can be constructed which
is unique to a particular fingerprint.
Comparison with a reference number for the individual takes only a fraction
of a second. Only the unique number is stored for each claimant; there is no
need to maintain politically sensitive files of fingerprints.
Takhar says his product cost Pounds 1m to develop. It combines the
techniques of 'neural networking' - high-speed computing similar to the way
some researchers believe the human brain operates - and 'fuzzy logic', which
allows answers between 'true' and 'false'.
These techniques are well understood. But eyebrows may be raised at Takhar's
claim that, in volume, he can sell a complete system, hardware and software,
for Dollars 300.
According to Brian Maitland Reynell, government services director of EDS:
'Takhar has contacted us. My technical people are very sceptical. Biometrics
is a very small world, and it seems highly unlikely that this man's system
would not have been heard of.
'They feel the mathematical probabilities are against him. However, we are
certainly prepared to take a look. We
would need to take the thing
apart and examine everything thoroughly.'
David Arnold, business development and marketing director at Thorn's
transaction (security card) division, says the same. 'Our technical people
have heard from him and have done a preliminary test, but they
would need to have a much closer look.'
Takhar shrugs off the derision. 'We expected disbelief. But we have got
international patents in place and now want to market our product.'
Asked why companies are not beating a path to his door, he replies: 'They
are. We only finalised the product last November and we wanted to make the
product known to the public before we approached the big companies.'
Takhar may be deluding himself, but as Reynell says: 'Stranger things have
happened. We are definitely interested in checking out the system.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Thorn Secure Systems.
    Electronic Data Systems Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3679 Electronic Components, NEC.
    P7372 Prepackaged Software.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
