<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): Card game with much
to play for - Banks may be victims of their own rules on issuing plastic
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE WORTHINGTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
On the basis that there is no such thing as a free lunch, the credit card
car discounts offered by Ford and General Motors in the UK must seem to many
people too good to be true. But consumers who choose their credit card well
and use it wisely can come out ahead of the game because of the peculiar
features of the credit card market.
Even after playing one dealer off against another in negotiations, GM and
Ford card holders can get a further healthy discount on the purchase of a
new car. This win-win situation has arisen because of the way the banks have
structured the credit card industry and organised its economics, possibly to
their own eventual detriment.
The structure of the industry is built around the two leading worldwide
credit card associations, Visa and MasterCard. They are 'owned' by the banks
that helped to establish them or subsequently joined them when they realised
the potential profitability of the market.
Membership of the card associations was originally restricted to banks but
competitive pressures led MasterCard in particular to relax its membership
criteria. It is still the case that only banks can become full members.
The card associations determine the procedures by which credit card
transactions are reconciled between card issuers, facilitate the
transmission of transaction information and set the fallback position on
pricing arrangements between card issuers, in the event of them being unable
to reach bilateral agreements.
The crucial element in this calculation is the so-called issuer
reimbursement fee (or interchange). This is an ad valorem amount paid on
every transaction by the bank that acquires these from the merchant, to the
bank that issued the card. The interchange rate on credit card transactions
varies between 1 per cent and 1.3 per cent, so that for a purchase of Pounds
100, between Pounds 1 and Pounds 1.30 is paid by the merchant where the
transaction took place to the acquirer bank, to be then passed on to the
issuing bank - where this is a different institution.
The acquiring bank requires recompense for the activities it undertakes; the
total cost to the merchant of a credit card transaction (including the
interchange rate) is called the merchant service charge and this is now an
average of around 1.7 per cent of the value of the card transaction.
The card association rules currently decree that only association members -
for which read banks - can be card transaction acquirers. The rewards are
particularly juicy for the banks that are large issuers and acquirers for
they handle many 'on-us' payments, where the acquired transaction is on
their issued card: here the merchant service charge can be allocated between
the acquirer and issuer sides of the bank, according to internal policies.
The four main clearing banks are believed to have more than 80 per cent of
the total combined issuing and acquiring market.
It is, however, the high level of interchange that has attracted the new
non-bank entrants to the credit card market, while dissuading a prominent
merchant, Marks and Spencer, from accepting Visa or MasterCard transactions.
For new entrants such as GM and Ford who can persuade their credit
cardholders to maximise spending on their credit cards, as indeed they must
to build up their car purchase rebate value, then as card issuers but not
acquirers they stand to receive a substantial and ongoing income stream
through the interchange arrangement. The income stream is activated as soon
as their credit cards are used by holders, whereas the rebates they offer
may well be cashed in some years into the future.
Added to this will be income paid to them under their agreement with their
issuing banks, HFC and Barclays respectively, as a proportion of interest
paid on cardholders' outstanding debt and on other card-related
income-generating activities, such as cash advances, credit card loss
protection, payment protection, fees for late payment and so on.
While such income does not entirely cover the rebate value accumulated by
their credit cardholders, it goes some considerable way towards offsetting
it. Who knows just how many rebates may not be cashed.
No wonder then that non-banks have sought to enter the credit card market
and that they can afford to offer cards with low APRs, no annual fees and
added-value features.
No wonder also that Marks and Spencer will continue not to accept Visa or
MasterCard credit cards or Amex or Diners charge cards and that other big
multiple retailers are thought to have been reconsidering their options on
this matter.
In an era of shrinking retail margins, but increasing spending through
credit cards, the proportion of the 1 to 1.3 per cent interchange not taken
by the card issuer can look very attractive.
Why are the card associations so reluctant to allow non-banks to become
members and why has the interchange rate been increased in recent years? The
answers lie in the banks' dual desires to protect their equity in the card
associations, while simultaneously milking that investment for cash, through
the interchange system.
The equity value of the card associations is unknown, but potentially
enormous, given their dominance of card-based payment systems worldwide. The
admission of non-banks as members would both dilute that equity and throw
into doubt the sustainability of the interchange charge, certainly at its
present rate.
Unfortunately for the banks, the consequences of not allowing non-banks to
join the card associations are potentially even more dangerous.
The car manufacturers and retailers have learnt that having a credit card
relationship with a customer is a key to wider and deeper relationships,
perhaps even to provide other financial services.
The GM and Ford credit cards offer those car manufacturers a regular,
justifiable and personal way to communicate with their cardholders via the
monthly statement.
By also using information from the cardholders' application form and by
monitoring their spending patterns, a great deal can be learnt about those
customers and their product and service needs.
Marks and Spencer's own credit card base has been the starting point for its
other incursions into financial services, Peps, personal loans and now
insurance and pensions.
Because of their narrow view of the profitability of credit cards and
failure to see the potential for wider relationship building, the banks have
often left their credit cards as standalone operations.
By either encouraging or allowing the interchange rate to be increased
disproportionately to the total amount of the merchant service charge, the
banks have made the issue of credit cards so economically attractive that
non-banks have seen how they can make money on the operation of a credit
card and build a card base that can be cross-sold with other products and
services.
Truly the banks are in great danger of being hoist by their own petard.
The author is a professor at Staffordshire University Business School.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6141 Personal Credit Institutions.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MGMT  Management &amp; Marketing.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
