<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): It's all in the name
 -Why Heinz and McVitie's are putting new emphasis on their brands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the coming weeks television viewers will see a subtle shift in the way a
number of leading consumer products are advertised in the UK. Instead of
emphasising the identities of the products themselves, manufacturers' own
names will be far more prominent than in recent years.
The move is part of the fightback by brand-owners against retailers'
own-label goods. It is also an attempt to consolidate expensive television
advertising behind just one message, rather than fragmenting it across the
promotion of numerous individual items.
Food companies Heinz and McVitie's are taking this route, while also
stepping up their direct marketing and promotion activities to reach
consumers with details of specific products.
Heinz, which currently spends an estimated Pounds 12m a year on television
advertising of individual products, including beans, soup and sauces, will
switch this money into supporting the main brand on television. The precise
nature of the commercials has still to be decided, but it is likely that
future campaigns will concentrate on what are seen to be fundamental Heinz
'values'.
The company has already used this approach with poster advertising, with an
umbrella campaign emphasising high nutritional content, lack of artificial
ingredients, and affordability.
With 300 products - around twice the number the company had a decade ago -
Heinz says it is increasingly difficult to promote individual lines through
mainstream advertising. Even tomato ketchup is no longer a straightforward
sell, as there are now half a dozen varieties.
This is where direct marketing can play its part, says Heinz, which is
planning a substantial investment in the direct targeting of particular
groups of consumers to promote individual products.
Lawrence Balfe, Heinz marketing director, says: 'While we remain totally
committed to advertising, with mainstream advertising expenditure staying at
current levels, we will be putting additional funds into our direct
communication activities. We see the direct link with our loyal consumers as
an essential means of developing our consumer franchise.'
The approach has already been successful over the last couple of years for
baby foods, the company claims, which represent a particularly tough
marketing challenge.
McVitie's direct contact with consumers will include a big free sample
drive, covering about 25 per cent of the UK population, and forms part of a
Pounds 20m push this year to strengthen the brand name.
For the first time in recent years McVitie's UK, the United Biscuits
subsidiary, is concentrating its advertising on the overall brand. An Pounds
8m TV campaign will cover four products: Digestive, Homewheat, Hob Nobs, and
Riva biscuits. Together they accounted for about Pounds 140m of McVitie's UK
turnover last year. The four brands will feature in the advertisements but
will not overshadow the McVitie's name.
A further Pounds 10m will be spent on in-store promotions and sampling,
while Pounds 1.5m will be spent on redesigning packaging to increase the
size of the McVitie's logo. The moves represent 'a fundamental change to the
McVitie's strategy,' says Andy Rush, marketing director. 'There is a clear
recognition in the business that our strongest asset is the McVitie's brand
and therefore all investment will be directed towards it in the future.'
United Biscuits, which has 44 per cent of the UK biscuit market, saw profits
on UK biscuits fall 10 per cent last year, before exceptionals, to Pounds
83.8m. This is partly attributable to a sharp increase in the cost of raw
materials, but the fact that McVitie's has had to trim margins is an
indication of the price pressure the company is under.
The pressure is coming from rival biscuit brands as well as retailers'
own-label products. Rush argues that smaller competitors' only strategic
option has been to compete on price. 'The key for us is not to follow them
down that route, but to maintain a quality stance in the marketplace,' he
says. Ensuring that advertising messages about the brand are not
inconsistent or dissipated among a whole range of products is central to
that strategy.
</TEXT>
