<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Conundrum of Birmingham property market's revival: A city
with a glut of office space cannot meet potential tenants' needs because
they are seeking air-conditioned premises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The commercial property market is poised for recovery. Rents have mostly
stopped falling, tenants are beginning to seek new premises and developers
are dusting down plans for new projects.
No single city is representative of the market as a whole. But many of the
factors driving the nascent recovery are evident in Birmingham. It has a
large number of empty buildings. About 800,000 sq ft of space is vacant in
Birmingham's core out of a total of about 16m sq ft. This year the amount of
empty, central space will rise to more than 1m sq ft as a result of
companies moving.
Paradoxically, there is insufficient space of the right kind to meet
tenants' demands. 'There is a general shortage of good-quality accommodation
of any size,' says Mr Andrew Wilkes, head of facilities and property at
Mercury Communications, which is seeking new premises of 120,000 sq ft in
Birmingham.
Like most other large prospective tenants, Mercury is reluctant to consider
the older buildings without air-conditioning - which make up the bulk of
Birmingham's empty stock of offices.
Modern property is in short supply in Birmingham. Unlike London, it does not
have a glut of space left from developments of the late 1980s. 'Birmingham
did not really benefit from the boom; the rents went up but the buildings
didn't,' says Mr Jon Bellfield, a director of Richardson Barberry, one of
the most active developers in the city.
The difficulty in finding space in Birmingham arises more from a scarcity of
good supply than from a large demand from potential tenants. Demand from
tenants is running at low levels, both because business confidence is
subdued and because of the difficulties of disposing of former premises. But
agents believe that if more buildings were available, there would be more
tenants seeking to move into them.
Richard Ellis says there are half a dozen companies that need more than
100,000 sq ft, although they are not actively looking for buildings because
so little of the right quality is available. A number of bidders for the
National Lottery looked at Birmingham, but were unavailable to find anything
suitable buildings.
The belief that a lack of the right supply has dampened demand is stirring
developers into action. The first speculative scheme is due to start next
month.
This will be the first building of Brindley Place, a 1.1m sq ft scheme close
to the International Convention Centre in the west of the city, outside the
inner ring road. Argent, which has already sold the building to an
institution, has yet to find a tenant, although it has been shortlisted by
Mercury.
The Fountains scheme in central Birmingham has planning consent for 90,000
sq ft of space by Axa Equity &amp; Law, the insurer. Richardson Barberry plans
to start in September on a 58,000 sq ft speculative office scheme in Temple
Street.
Apart from Brindley Place, the largest potential project in central
Birmingham is adjacent to Snow Hill Station, where Speyhawk, a developer
which collapsed last year, had planned a 900,000 sq ft building. British
Rail Property Board and the city's Economic Development Department, the
site's owners, are seeking a new developer.
Problems experienced by property owners in letting obsolescent buildings
provides a powerful incentive for redevelopment. The enthusiasm with which
developers are pursuing their plans begs the question of whether Birmingham
 -which has 3m sq ft of valid planning permits - could end up with an
oversupply of new space that will depress rents.
Mr Andrew Causer, an analyst at brokers James Capel, believes not. He argues
that the development pipeline is not big enough to prevent rents from rising
from their current level of about Pounds 20 per sq ft towards Pounds 25 per
sq ft over the next three years.
Mr Bellfield agrees, pointing out that only cash-rich investors or
institutions are willing to build speculatively. Most developers are anxious
to secure a commitment from a potential tenant before beginning work.
'If everyone with a site started to build tomorrow, that might create an
oversupply, but that is unlikely to happen,' he says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
