<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Record profit at Post Office
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Post Office made a record operating profit last year, Mr Bill Cockburn,
chief executive, said yesterday.
Although the full results will not be announced until next month Mr Cockburn
said they were 'excellent' in a year that saw the largest volume of mail
distribution ever recorded.
He said that the corporation faced growing competition to its services
however and needed an urgent decision from the government over whether it
could enjoy commercial freedom and not be hemmed in by public-sector
financial requirements set by the Treasury.
The Post Office's hands were being tied by the government's delay on the
future of the organisation, he said. This was enabling the Dutch postal
service - to be privatised next month - and possibly the German one to
'plunder' the British market, he added.
'Unless we can respond on equal terms at Post Office counters, up to 20 per
cent of our business could be at risk over the next few years and with it
30,000 jobs and the closure of up to 5,000 Post Offices.'
Mr Cockburn also announced the results of a public opinion survey in which
76 per cent of the consumers questioned said they supported making the Post
Office free to enter new markets and offer new services to compete with
electronic communications.
Two-thirds of respondents supported the suggestion that the Post Office
should be able to compete with banks and building societies and 61 per cent
agreed it should be free to raise money to invest in its business.
However, the survey, carried out by Opinion Research and Communication,
found strong opposition to suggestions that the Post Office should be
privatised. While 49 per cent favoured allowing the organisation freedom to
enter and invest in new markets, they also thought the taxpayer should
remain as the sole shareholder.
From the sample of 1,068 adults aged 16 and over at a hundred sampling
points, 42 per cent disagreed that the service to the ordinary customer
would be good or better under a privatised postal service.
</TEXT>
