FT  05 MAY 94 / Treasury expects recovery to continue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Treasury yesterday presented a favourable picture of UK economic
developments to coincide with the monthly monetary meeting between Mr
Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Eddie George, the governor of the
Bank of England.
In its latest monthly report, prepared for the meeting, the Treasury noted
that Britain's latest monthly economic indicators remained consistent with
continuing recovery, and retail sales 'remained on a strong upward trend'.
Although the report merely compiled recent economic data and gave no new
insights into the thinking of policymakers, it added to the impression that
yesterday's meeting was not the occasion for a decision to change monetary
policy.
Expectations of a cut in bank base rates from 5.25 per cent have been
receding for some time, with some commentators now suggesting that the next
move could be upwards.
Britain's gold and currency reserves rose an underlying Dollars 19m in April
according to Treasury figures released yesterday. The overall level of
official reserves rose by Dollars 531m to Dollars 43,446m at the end of
April from Dollars 42,915m at the end of March.
