<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Large National Insurance shortfalls found
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Employers appear to be underpaying National Insurance contributions due on
their employees' company cars to the tune of more than Pounds 240m a year,
the National Audit Office says in a report published today.
The public expenditure watchdog reports that fewer than half of 10,000
employers surveyed were paying the right amount. Underpayments averaged 36
per cent of the amount due.
The audit office has qualified the accounts of the National Insurance fund
because of uncertainties over the amounts of contributions underpaid.
However, the Contributions Agency, responsible for collecting National
Insurance, said last night that the underpayments were still being pursued.
Underpaid contributions can be pursued for up to six years after they are
due.
Employers are liable to pay Class 1A contributions on the cash equivalent
benefit of cars and car fuel provided to employees. About half the money is
paid direct to the Contributions Agency, the rest collected through PAYE by
the Inland Revenue.
The Revenue has been unable to modify its computer systems to separate Class
1A contributions from other National Insurance contributions. The National
Insurance accounts are therefore based on an estimate by the Government
Actuary of Pounds 429m for the amount collected in Class 1A contributions.
The Contributions Agency wants to use company car declarations provided to
the Inland Revenue by employers to check that the right amount of National
Insurance has been paid.
It is also compiling a register of employers to assist in checks. In
addition to monitoring Class 1A contributions, the register will be used to
ensure that employers deduct and pay the right amount of Class 1
contributions on employees' earnings.
The agency's inspectors discovered underpayments in Class 1 contributions of
some Pounds 89m on visits to 118,000 employers. Inland Revenue staff
checking PAYE records discovered Pounds 48m of underpayments on 46,000
inspection visits.
But since employers' visits are targeted on high-risk businesses, the agency
is unable to quantify the overall level of error in contribution receipts.
The accounts have also been qualified over uncertainties experienced in
previous years in the amounts employers are paying out in statutory sick pay
and statutory maternity pay. The agency plans a survey of employers to
determine whether correct amounts are paid out.
The level of errors in unemployment benefit payments were also censured by
the NAO.
</TEXT>
