<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / SIB chairman issues warning to companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The option of being regulated directly by the Securities and Investments
Board, the City's chief watchdog, should not be available indefinitely to
financial services companies, Mr Andrew Large, chairman of the Securities
and Investments Board indicated to MPs yesterday.
He said the ability of a company to choose to be regulated by SIB should be
reviewed once the Personal Investment Authority, the new regulator to
protect the private investor, had been established.
Mr Large told the Commons Treasury committee that he wanted the PIA to
become operational as a regulator 'before and without' removing the choice
of regulator available under the financial services legislation, but that
once the new regulator had come into effect then that aspect of the 1986 act
should be looked at again.
His evidence to the committee's inquiry into financial regulation seemed to
be aimed directly at reassuring the MPs about the effectiveness of the PIA
after weeks in which they have heard several witnesses suggesting that the
proposals will not work. Meanwhile, the MPs themselves have sounded
sceptical about its prospects.
In particular, Mr Large was forced to defend Mr Joe Palmer whose appointment
as PIA chairman has caused some MPs to express concern. Mr Palmer was
formerly chief executive of Legal &amp; General, which recently attracted a then
record fine from Lautro, the existing regulator for the life insurance
industry, for systemic failures in its compliance arrangements.
Mr Large was pressed by Mr Brian Sedgemore, a Labour committee member, about
Mr Palmer's answers to the committee last week.
The day after giving evidence to the committee, Mr Palmer wrote apologising
for having inadvertently misled MPs by saying that he had not seen an
internal Legal &amp; General memorandum from 1990, which suggested there were
widespread breaches of the rules by sales consultants.
Mr Large also indicated the timetable for the regulatory switch to the PIA.
He said that SIB would decide next month whether finally and formally to
recognise PIA as a regulator.
The PIA is due to become operational in July.
At the same time, SIB would decide whether to withdraw recognition from
Lautro and from Fimbra, the existing regulator for independent financial
advisers.
A likely timescale would be for the watchdogs to stop accepting new
companies from the beginning of October, but to continue for about a year to
regulate existing companies which had not transferred to the PIA.
</TEXT>
