<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Audience deserted Accountancy TV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Accountancy Television, the training service for accountants, had only 200
subscribers to its programmes broadcast on the BBC Select Service when it
collapsed last month, it emerged yesterday.
There were just 867 names in total for the list of TV and video subscribers,
bought yesterday for Pounds 40,000 from the receivers by Television
Education Network (TEN), its leading competitor since launch two years ago.
The customer figures are much lower than earlier claims by Accountancy
Television that it had 1,200 subscribers, and indicate the extent of the
company's financial crisis.
Initial reports prepared by the receivers from accountants Buchler Phillips
suggest the service has lost more than Pounds 1.5m since it opened and owes
creditors more than Pounds 350,000.
The collapse has proved embarrassing to its backers BBC Select, BPP, the
financial training company, and five of the UK's six leading professional
accountancy bodies.
TEN yesterday said that it would send Accountancy Television customers its
own videos until their subscriptions expired.
Observer, Page 25
