<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Efficiency of Child Support Agency in doubt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Child Support Agency may collect no more in maintenance payments from
absent parents in its first year than the Department of Social Security
collected last year.
The disclosure, which emerged this week in answer to MPs' questions, will be
politically damaging for the government since it suggests, by one yardstick,
that the controversial new regime is no more effective than the old.
It comes just two weeks after it was revealed that the agency is more than
Pounds 100m short of its overall target of making benefit savings of Pounds
530m for 1993-94.
With figures for one month of its financial year still to come, the benefit
savings secured by the agency have reached just Pounds 285m.
This compares with Pounds 313m in savings secured in 1992-93. The agency is
confident that it will beat this figure.
In a further disclosure, Ms Ros Hepplewhite, the agency's chief executive,
has told Mr Frank Field, Labour chairman of the Commons social security
committee, that the cost of setting up the agency was 'around Pounds 146m'
and that its running costs 'are estimated at Pounds 97.8m'.
The committee is to launch a review of the agency's workings when it
receives the body's annual report, expected in July. The committee expects
to publish its second report on the agency in the autumn.
According to figures released by Ms Hepplewhite, the agency collected a
total of Pounds 186m in maintenance payments in the 11 months to the end of
February. This compares with Pounds 220m in maintenance obtained by the DSS
in 1992-93 for income support claimants.
To match that performance this year the agency would need to have collected
Pounds 34m in March, the last month of its financial year, for which figures
are not yet available. This would be exactly double the Pounds 17m it
secured in February.
The agency said yesterday that the maintenance collection figures for
1992-93 and 1993-94 were not directly comparable, since it now deals with a
larger client group than the DSS had done.
The agency now handles family credit recipients and private clients in
addition to income support claimants.
Ministers put the agency's disappointing financial performance down to
changes forced by the social security committee and a refusal by some
fathers to pay maintenance.
In February, the DSS responded to Commons criticism of the agency by
amending the formula for absent parents' maintenance payments. The changes
also allowed fathers facing big bills to pay in stages over an 18-month
period.
Mr Field said recently that he felt the anger expressed by the public
necessitated a new inquiry to decide whether the formula that determined how
much parents should pay ought to be changed.
In a letter to Mr Field last month, Mr Peter Lilley, social security
secretary, said he was 'determined not to be rushed into further,
inappropriate changes simply because the policy is unpopular with some
sections of the community'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9441 Administration of Social and Manpower Programs.
</IN>
