<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Labour confident of true-blue Redbridge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Three weeks ago Miss Liz Pearce, Labour leader on Redbridge council, was
quietly accepting that the Tories would retain control of the borough, which
they have run without break for 30 years.
But her opinion changed this week. 'I am confident that the Tories will lose
overall control here,' she says, running through a list of promising canvass
returns in the north-east London borough. 'I think we have a very good
chance of winning outright.'
Miss Pearce's prediction should cause deep anxiety among party workers at
Tory central office as they ponder how the elections in London will go
today.
Redbridge, where the Tory group has a majority of 23 seats, ought to be
impossible to lose. Psephologists claim it is 'on the cusp' between a bad
result for the Tories and a disastrous one.
If Redbridge goes, the Tories will only have the big strongholds of
Wandsworth, Westminster and Kensington left.
The borough of Redbridge, combining towns such as Ilford, Wanstead and
Woodford, is classic Thatcherite territory. It has many white, aspiring
middle-class voters, who have been the bedrock of conservatism in the last
20 years.
The council leadership has been composed of a closely-knit group of Tories
who were all elected to the council 20 years ago. Yet Labour seems to have
made huge inroads here in the last few days.
Miss Pearce claims that in some marginal wards Labour is getting the support
of between 50 and 60 per cent of those who say they will vote.
She claims that 90 per cent of first-time voters are opting for Labour.
Even in Wanstead and Woodford, Sir Winston Churchill's constituency for many
years, Labour candidates are supported by a remarkable 42 per cent of those
who say they will vote.
Tory campaigners are still confident that they will win. They privately
admit that the party will lose 9 seats on the council, but this will still
give them a majority of 5.
Mr Ronnie Barden, the Tory group leader, believes that the predictions of
Labour victory are no different from those that were made - in error - in
1990.
'People may say on the doorstep that they will vote Labour,' he says. 'But,
time and again, when they come to the ballot box they have second thoughts.'
</TEXT>
