<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Poisoning claims near settlement
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
More than 150 people who claim their health was affected in Britain's
biggest water poisoning incident are close to a cash settlement. Their
claims for damages stemming from the Camelford water affair were adjourned
at Truro Crown Court yesterday.
Mr John Hendy QC, representing 10 people chosen to make test claims against
South West Water Services, told Mr Justice Wright: 'The parties are speaking
to each other. Some progress has been made and it is likely more progress
will be made with an adjournment.'
The case was expected to last three weeks before moving to London but a cash
settlement is now likely to be offered to the 159 claimants.
The case comes six years after 20 tonnes of aluminium sulphate was poured
into the wrong tank at the Lowermoor treatment works near Camelford,
Cornwall.
