<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / World Trade News: US hits at barriers to film, TV exports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US audio-visual industry, the country's second largest exporter, claims
it is under siege around the world, fettered by quotas, discriminated
against by tax laws and a target for pirates who sell illegal duplicates of
films and television programmes.
This, at least, is the contention of the Motion Picture Export Association,
and its colourful chairman, Mr Jack Valenti, who in a new report cites what
he says is a 'catalogue of artificial barriers erected by governments on
every continent, whose aim is to shrink the reach of American visual
entertainment and to baffle the movement of our products in world market
places.'
According to MPEAA, China's piracy costs the US industry an estimated
Dollars 40m (Pounds 26.5m) in exports; it has also thrown up 'a vast array
of market restrictions' to legitimate US exports. Until recently there were
few pirate videos of US products in China, according to a US lawyer. But the
market has grown with rising purchases of VCRs. Political relaxation has
made enforcement a more important issue.
Europe remains the film industry's largest market, which is why 'cultural
protectionism' which limits US TV programming has become a live issue. Italy
and Turkey were singled out for 'continuous and unacceptably high levels of
piracy exacerbated by lack of legal protection and insufficient penalties
for enfringement.'
Piracy is also a problem in Poland and Hungary along with concerns on
currency convertibility, freedom to remit earnings and distribute filmed
entertainment with minimal government control.
In Latin America, there are worries about 'an emerging trend' toward use of
revenues from the sale of foreign films to support the national industry.
The Middle East has become 'a transshipment centre' for pirated products.
A long crusade on intellectual property rights has won the industry powerful
Washington friends in both Congress and the White House. Hollywood campaigns
for politicians and helps finance their campaign. Film directors, such as Mr
Steven Spielberg and Mr Martin Scorsese, issued statements equating artistic
freedom with open markets.
Even clout could not contend with the intricacies of US-China trade
relations. When the deadline came for Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade
representative, to release the Special 301 lists designating countries for
talks and potential sanctions for intellectual property rights violations,
naming of China as a 'priority foreign country' was delayed until June 30.
Mr Valenti expressed disappointment. 'It is an open and shut case,' he said.
'Piracy in China is visible and confirmable.'
Inclusion of intellectual property rights in the planned new World Trade
Organisation, if it is approved, will allow the US to take many of these
complaints to a multilateral forum. But, according to the US lawyer, the US
will still have to sometimes act unilaterally because 'even copyright laws
consistent with the WTO may not be adequate because of advances in
technology.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
