<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / World Trade News: Rolls-Royce set to secure Saudia order
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rolls-Royce could win a significant piece of the Dollars 6.2bn (Pounds
4.1bn) fleet renewal and expansion programme by Saudia, the Saudi Arabian
national carrier, by supplying it with engines for its US-built Boeing
widebody airliners.
If confirmed, the engine order would represent a consolation prize for
Europe, which in February was dealt a heavy blow by the Saudi government
when it opted for Boeing and McDonnell Douglas aircraft to modernise
Saudia's fleet.
The European Airbus consortium had hoped to win a large slice of the Saudia
order but in what was seen as a highly political decision after an
unprecedented degree of US government export promotion, the Saudi government
said it intended to buy only US-built airliners.
Saudia has been holding complex talks with the two US aircraft manufacturers
during the past six weeks to select the number and types of airliners for
its fleet modernisation programme.
The airline is now drawing up a report to be submitted to its government
recommending the purchase of a total of 61 airliners, including Boeing 737
twin engine narrowbody aircraft, Boeing 747 four engine and 777 twin engine
widebody airliners and McDonnell Douglas MD11 three engine widebody
aircraft, according to the Saudi al-Hayat newspaper.
The Saudi government is expected to take a final decision on the huge order
this summer. The US Export-Import Bank has already said it would guarantee
Dollars 6.2bn financing for the deal.
Quoting informed sources, the newspaper said Saudia had also recommended the
selection of engines to power its new aircraft.
It said General Electric of the US was expected to take 46 per cent of the
engine package, with Pratt &amp; Whitney of the US taking 26 per cent and
Rolls-Royce of the UK taking 28 per cent.
Since the UK group does not build engines for the Boeing 737 or the MD11,
its potential order would involve supplying powerplants for the Boeing 747
and 777 widebody airliners.
Rolls-Royce yesterday declined to comment on the newspaper report.
Although the deal would represent an important breakthrough for Rolls-Royce
and its new Trent 800 large engine designed for the new Boeing 777, it risks
sparking some resentment in European aerospace industry circles.
French aerospace officials have often criticised in private what they regard
is the UK government's ambivalent stance in promoting European commercial
aerospace exports. They suggest the UK has tended to favour Rolls-Royce,
whose engines at present equip more Boeing than Airbus aircraft, rather than
Airbus in which British Aerospace has a 20 per cent stake.
This reflects the relatively higher UK value of a Boeing aircraft equiped by
Rolls-Royce engines compared with an Airbus aircraft equipped with a US
power plant.
Engines account for about 20-25 per cent of the value of an airliner but
they also produce considerable additional long term revenues from sales of
spare parts, aerospace analysts note.
However, the UK value of an Airbus aircraft with Rolls-Royce engines such as
the A330, the new twin engine Airbus widebody offered but not selected by
Saudia, rises to around 50 per cent.
</TEXT>
