<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Menem scraps pension plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Argentina's President Carlos Menem has scrapped a controversial provision
forcing the country's biggest bank, government-owned Banco de la Nacion
Argentina (BNA), to offer dollar-linked pension funds.
The government argued the change was needed to remove a big distortion from
its pension reforms, but it has led to protests that Mr Menem is ruling by
personal fiat. The provision was approved last year by Congress and the
president's right to issue decrees was originally intended for use in
emergencies only.
On Tuesday Mr Menem decreed BNA need not provide a minimum dollar-linked
return for retirement savings accounts it will administer on behalf of
private savers.
Argentina is just beginning to implement a private pension fund system to
complement the bankrupt state pay-as-you-go system. Savers must choose
between staying in the state system or picking companies to manage their
individual retirement accounts.
Mr Menem's Peronist government last year had to accept a Peronist demand
that BNA offer dollar-linked pension schemes as the party's price for
supporting pension reform. But rival pension managers complained this gave
BNA an unfair advantage.
However, Mr Jorge Matzkin, Peronist party leader in Congress, yesterday
warned the decree was 'not the most adequate way of eliminating the
guarantee. We will present a bill offering substitute guarantees better than
those removed.'
Pension reform will channel Dollars 200m a month into the capital markets
but it has been dogged by poor organisation.
The government only allowed fund managers to begin selling pension plans on
Monday. They have until the end of July to sign up the 5m workers eligible
for the system.
</TEXT>
