<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Inflation dashes Brazilian hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Inflation in Brazil's new currency-in-waiting accelerated sharply in April
in a blow to government hopes of containing price rises.
Monthly inflation in the URV accounting unit increased nearly a percentage
point to 2.62 per cent in April from 1.77 per cent in March, according to
Fipe, one of the country's main research institutes.
The URV, or unit of real value, was introduced in March as the first step
towards the creation of a new currency, the real, which the government
expects to launch in July.
Government economists said prices remained volatile, and sharp swings are
expected until the new currency is fully in place. They claimed some prices
were falling in URV terms, but indicators had not yet registered it.
Inflation is continuing to soar in underlying cruzeiro prices. Fipe said
yesterday April cruzeiro inflation rose to 46.22 per cent from 41.94 per
cent in March. If this rate of increase continues, Brazil will soon pass
through the technical measure of hyperinflation, 50 per cent a month.
</TEXT>
