<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Gaza-Jericho Autonomy: Decades of neglect leave unemployment
as the norm - The economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Groups of young men sit outside their concrete breeze-block shacks in the
middle of the day in the sprawling rubbish streets of Jabalya refugee camp
in the occupied Gaza Strip. For many Palestinian youths, unemployment is the
expected norm.
Creating jobs for the 800,000 residents of the Strip, where 40-50 per cent
of the workforce is unemployed and the population is growing at 4.6 per cent
a year, will be the immediate challenge for the incoming Palestinian
authority.
The Palestinians will also need to reverse decades of Egyptian and Israeli
neglect which have left Gaza's sewerage, water, roads, power, communications
and housing in disrepair and chaos. The World Bank says the Israeli-run
civil administration of the occupied territories for 27 years had an
unusually low rate of investment, only 3 per cent of gross domestic product.
A recent International Labour Organisation report warned unemployment could
worsen unless the Palestinian administration puts in place an immediate
programme for up to 12,000 freed detainees, along with temporary public
works measures to employ a further 15,000 workers.
Many of Gaza's problems are repeated in Jericho and the West Bank. But Gaza,
which has an annual per capita income of Dollars 850 (Pounds 566), will be
the real test for the economic challenges of peace. Unless Gazans feels a
rapid change in living standards, the already fragile support for the peace
process may collapse. Unmet expectations may fuel Islamic and other groups
which reject peace with Israel.
'If the peace process is to have any hope of success, the Palestinians need
to see improvements in the living conditions quickly,' Mr Caio Koch-Weser,
World Bank vice president, said this week.
Total GDP for the West Bank and Gaza Strip is Dollars 3bn, less than 5 per
cent of the Israeli economy. Creating economic growth will not be easy.
First, the Palestinians must untangle a web of regulations over investment,
land and trade which scared away private-sector investment. The biggest
factory in the Gaza Strip is the Seven-Up bottling company, and industry's
share of GDP is less than 10 per cent. Second, the Palestinians must create
credible economic institutions free from the political interference of the
PLO.
The economic protocol with Israel will considerably aid the Palestinians in
giving them access to the huge market next door. Mr Samir Houleila, a
Palestinian economist, says the agreement will create an immediate lowering
in costs of production and living.
This is because Palestinians have won a lower rate of VAT and direct
taxation, lower customs duties on many imports mainly for construction, and
cheaper sources of oil which will let them price petroleum products freely -
except petrol which can be only 15 per cent lower than Israeli pump prices.
In agriculture, which accounts for at least a quarter of Palestinian GDP,
the economic accord grants Palestinians the right to export to Israel for
the first time since 1967. All farm products will be exported freely except
for five items subject to a sliding quota scale until 1999. Lower labour and
production costs should let Palestinians compete effectively with Israeli
farmers.
The Palestinians will also be much helped by a Dollars 1.2bn, three-year
emergency aid programme announced by the World Bank this week. About half
the package, which will inject Dollars 200 a year in aid per person, is
targeted on transport, water supply, housing and education.
International donors are increasingly concerned about the Palestinian
ability to absorb the aid, spend it on productive projects and create the
capacity to manage their own economy. The World Bank's report acknowledges
the risk that some aid could end up being used for 'political' construction
projects that are not needed and line the pockets of politically-connected
businessmen.
Institutions such as the Palestinian Economic Council for Development and
Reconstruction, which will co-ordinate aid with donors, will be play a vital
role. Senior Palestinian economists fear the PLO may not allow independent
and efficient institutions to emerge.
'The problem for the PLO is to realise that it is no longer in exile and
needs different capacity, different organisational structure based on
efficiency, professionalism and transparency,' said Mr Houleila.
Another problem is skills gaps in the occupied territories, especially in
economic and financial management. Mr Houleila said recent efforts to
recruit personnel from the Arab world have been a failure; he urged Arab
governments to give key workers a sabbatical to work in Gaza-Jericho for a
year. Foreign technical assistance and training programmes, such as Bank of
England assistance with the Palestinian Monetary Authority, will be
critical.
Raising their own revenue, building an independent sustainable base to
finance domestic activities and avoiding aid dependence will be a vital
challenge. Israel will help by transferring 75 per cent of income tax levied
on Palestinian migrant workers in Israel to the 'Palestinian treasury'. But
improving tax collection in Gaza-Jericho will not be easy.
Ultimately, much will depend on the Palestinians building a stable free
market environment to attract the billions of dollars held by the
Palestinian business diaspora.
</TEXT>
<XX>
