<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / ADB loans policy angers Asians
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALEXANDER NICOLL, Asia Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NICE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Asian developing countries yesterday made public their bitterness at the
linkage of a capital increase for the Asian Development Bank to new lending
policies.
A doubling of the bank's capital to Dollars 46bn (Pounds 30.6bn) is almost
certain to be formally approved by May 22 by countries holding at least 75
per cent of shares. But China has abstained from the vote and other
countries are approving it only, while recording their concern.
Industrialised countries, led by the US, have insisted that the capital
increase be linked to a switch in focus of ADB lending to issues such as
poverty and the environment. They have also linked lending to the concept of
'good governance', which, to developing countries, smacks of political
interference.
Mr Zhou Zhengqing, senior Chinese official attending the ADB's annual
meeting in Nice, said: 'China does not agree with the linkage between policy
and capital; they are totally different issues.' China viewed the change
with the 'greatest regret' and linking projects to the solution of social
problems was 'not helpful'.
China and other countries believe that ADB lending to infrastructural
projects fosters development and economic growth which, in turn, leads to
the solution of social problems.
Mr Roger Altman, deputy US Treasury Secretary, insisted the changes were in
line with those made at other multilateral development banks and reflected
the maturing of the region. 'Private capital flows have risen to the point
where financing of projects can now be absorbed by the private sector,' he
said in an interview.
'It is not as if social-sector lending doesn't have an economic pay-off,' he
added, arguing that lending to support education and health care had
longer-term economic benefits. The ADB should not, however, compete with
private-sector lending or substitute for it.
US officials said that they expected the guidelines to be applied 'flexibly
and pragmatically' and that the ADB would still have the scope to respond to
the disparate needs of borrowing members. Mr Altman declined to define 'good
governance', saying it was 'one of those things you know when you see.
There's no short answer to that question.'
Mr Mar'ie Muhammad, Indonesia's finance minister, said it was 'impractical
and unrealistic to try to devise an all-embracing set of policies for all
member countries.'
Thailand and India also expressed concern about the linkage of capital to
lending policy. Mr Mohammad Saifur Rahman, finance minister of Bangladesh,
said a majority of the ADB's developing members had been against it. 'We
wish the exercise could have been conducted in a more subtle manner,
avoiding this division,' he added.
Mr Ian de Jong, representing the Netherlands, defended the change as common
practice in international financial institutions.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
</CN>
