<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / ANC farm policy stresses market pricing strategies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The African National Congress yesterday launched an agricultural policy
paper combining market-driven pricing strategies, a competitive exchange
rate to encourage exports, and a big increase in support for small farmers.
'We firmly believe market principles should determine prices,' Mr Derek
Hanekom, ANC agriculture spokesman, said, explaining the farming ideas the
ANC expects will form the basis of future government policy. But the paper
maintains a cautious approach to the sensitive issue of land redistribution.
The 60-page document says these and other policies 'will be implemented in
the context of a programme of land reform and rural development designed to
redistribute land to alleviate landlessness, land hunger and apartheid
dispossession'.
The land reform programme will involve both the 'restitution of land to the
victims of forced removals since 1913 through a Land Claims Court, and a
process of land redistribution to assist those with limited means denied
access to land under apartheid laws.'
But the paper does not depart from the principles set out in the ANC's main
economic policy document, The Reconstruction and Development Programme. This
calls on the government to provide 'substantial funds' for land
redistribution, but within the framework of the new constitution which
allows for expropriation but stipulates there shall be fair compensation.
South Africa's 50,000 commercial farmers, almost all white, are the main
users of the country's agricultural support services, the paper notes. About
30 per cent of them are responsible for 80 per cent of the country's farm
output.
Small-scale farming has been neglected or undermined, and one of the key
elements of ANC agricultural policy is the creation of a more diversified
farming community by supporting this sector, in part by 'modifying'
agricultural credit policies and reviewing the role of the Land Bank.
'Credit subsidies and bail-out to help commercial farmers must stop,' the
paper warns. 'Public-finance institutions should rapidly begin to redirect
grants and lending to poor farmers in consultation with local communities.'
High price incentives, input subsidies and protective import barriers cost
the consumer and taxpayer about Rand 2bn (Pounds 377m) a year, the paper
calculates. While world food prices remain depressed, the case for reducing
levels of protection as part of a broad food policy remains strong, it adds.
But the report also says 'additional food subsidies should be considered',
singling out maize and bread as the most important foodstuffs. The ANC
intends to 'remove most of the remaining statutory powers of agricultural
control boards', it goes on.
Uniform national pricing will disappear, while 'a greater emphasis will be
placed on market forces, bringing domestic producer prices more in line with
international markets'.
For the 'more strategic commodities such as maize', a state-supported
marketing agency will be required to serve the buyer of last resort through
operation of a floor price system. The floor price would be pitched at a low
level, only slightly above export parity.
Agricultural exports incentives, 'limited to a specific time period and
related to performance', will be used to increase export earnings.
'Macro-economic policy will also be important to avoid sustained currency
over-valuation and promote the competitiveness of South African
agriculture.'
</TEXT>
