FT  05 MAY 94 / Drug inquiry hits Thai MP
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BANGKOK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Thai government is investigating allegations that an opposition member
of parliament has been involved in drug trafficking to the US, it said
yesterday. The disclosure is the latest in a series of embarrassing drug
scandals involving Thai politicians.
Mr Den Tohmeena, deputy interior minister, said he would visit the US this
week to seek details of the accusations against Mr Thanong Siripreechapong,
an MP for the Chart Thai party, in talks with the US Drug Enforcement
Administration.
A US court last year ordered the seizure of Mr Thanong's Los Angeles home
and a Mercedes Benz car on the grounds they had been bought with profits
from narcotics smuggling. According to a US prosecutor, Mr Thanong earned
more than Dollars 10m (Pounds 6.6m) by arranging marijuana shipments to the
US. Efforts to contact Mr Thanong yesterday were unsuccessful.
Thai drug enforcement officials said yesterday that the US had asked the
Thais to freeze the MP's assets in Thailand as well, but the US embassy in
Bangkok could not confirm this. Western diplomats said the Thai authorities
could seize assets under Thai law, but the US had simply asked the
government to notify Mr Thanong of the seizure of his US assets.
The timing of the accusations surfacing in the Thai press this week against
Mr Thanong is convenient for the coalition government (its efforts to reform
the constitution are being blocked by the opposition parties), but Mr
Thanong is not the first Thai politician against whom such allegations have
been made.
Two years ago, Mr Narong Wongwan, a powerful businessman refused entry to
the US because of his alleged links to heroin trafficking, was nominated by
a group of pro-military parties as prime minister. But the accusations
stopped him gaining the job.
</TEXT>
