<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 94 / Greek economy post filled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Yannos Papantoniou, 45, a British-trained economist, yesterday took over
as Greece's economy minister, following the death of Mr Giorgos Gennimatas.
His appointment signalled that there will be no tightening of economic
policy, despite European Commission calls for immediate spending cuts to
reduce the public sector deficit. This year's government borrowing
requirement is projected at more than 17 per cent of gross domestic product,
against a budget target of 12.8 per cent. A technocrat with few close
friends in the governing Panhellenic Socialist Movement, Mr Papantoniou
lacks the authority to impose overdue but unpopular measures, such as
freezing recruitment in the public sector. He could also face problems
launching the flotation of OTE, the state telecoms company.
