<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Weakness in sterling and gilts, higher than anticipated money supply figures
together with political uncertainty in the UK combined to cast a shadow over
the derivatives sector, writes Joel Kibazo.
In futures, traders initially attributed the poor opening in the June
contract on the FT-SE at 3,129 to a 'correction' after Friday's strong
finish. Light buying in the first hour saw the contract touch 3,140 but this
faded after the release of the money supply data. The figures were higher
than anticipated, increasing doubts about a further reduction in UK interest
rates.
The decline of sterling and the retreat in bonds increased the selling
pressure, as did nervousness about the outcome of tomorrow's local elections
in the UK. It left June to trade at a substantial discount to cash for a
large part of the session. Monument Securities and Goldman Sachs were said
to have been among the day's main sellers.
June closed at 3,091, down 43 on its previous close. Volume was 12,878. The
June mid 250 contract finished at 3,760 after trade of 101 lots.
Traded options were particularly dull with a mere 21,119 lots dealt by the
close. Volume in the FT-SE 100 option was 6,818 contracts and 1,547 in the
Euro FT-SE 100 option. HSBC was the most active stock option with a total of
2,163 lots dealt.
