<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / World Stock Markets (America): US gains on news of Kodak
restructuring
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Blue-chip stocks improved as news of Kodak's restructuring and a second big
healthcare acquisition provided a diversion from lingering concerns over
interest rates, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 13.39 higher at 3,714.41, climbing
back from an 18-point deficit during the afternoon. The more broadly based
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 inched 0.01 ahead to 453.03, even though declining
issues led advances, 1,093 to 985, in thin trading.
In the secondary markets, the American SE composite was 2.19 better at
442.39, but the Nasdaq composite eased 1.31 to 739.37.
Stocks meandered in a narrow range on either side of their opening levels
during the morning.
The day's only fresh economic news - the March index of leading indicators -
came in a little higher than expected, but not enough to spark any sustained
buying and selling.
Developments in the bond market were not encouraging, as the 30-year
benchmark government issue slipped again. But trading was thin, with many
accounts remaining on the sidelines ahead Friday's employment data for
April, a keenly awaited barometer of economic strength and inflationary
pressures.
The overall mood was subdued, with the Federal Reserve's next move to lift
rates expected soon.
Later in the afternoon, a fresh decline by the dollar against the yen and
D-mark hit bonds and in turn share prices. But both markets recovered
quickly, and the blue chips pushed well into positive ground in the final
hour of trading.
Kodak brought some cheer to what could have been a rather dull market. The
stock climbed Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 46 1/8 after announcing that it would
sell-off three non-core businesses, including its Sterling Winthrop
over-the-counter drug subsidiary.
It was the second consecutive session driven by news in the pharmaceuticals
sector. Syntex, whose share price jumped on Monday on the announcement of
Roche's Dollars 5.3bn bid, was again on top of the NYSE's most active list,
ebbing Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 23 3/8 .
Yesterday also brought news that United Healthcare, one of the biggest
health maintenance organisations, had agreed to sell its drug-distribution
business to SmithKline Beecham for Dollars 2.3bn. The announcement pushed
United Dollars 2 3/8 higher to Dollars 46 1/2 . Elsewhere, Value Health
jumped Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 44 1/2 after agreeing to form a 'strategic
relationship' with Pfizer.
Time Warner gained Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 39 1/4 amid speculation that the
company was ripe for takeover.
On the Nasdaq, technology stocks retreated following the previous session's
upturn. Wellfleet lost Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 75 1/4 , Microsoft shed
Dollars 2 to Dollars 93 1/2 and Lotus Development dropped Dollars 1 7/8 to
Dollars 63 7/8 .
Canada
Toronto prices closed mixed in relatively light trading. The TSE-300
composite index rose 1.28 points, or 0.03 per cent, to close at 4,283.61.
But declining issues outnumbered advances 396 to 321.
Volume was 58.66m shares, down from Monday's record 109.35m, but trading
value rose to CDollars 552.4m from CDollars 548.6m.
The conglomerates group had the day's biggest decline, off 1.2%. The mining,
gold and industrial products groups also finished lower.
</TEXT>
