<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / International Company News: IBM steps up battle for
mid-range market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
International Business Machines yesterday fired the latest salvo in the
battle for the important mid-range computer market.
It launched the latest version of its AS/400 mid-range computer family with
the claim that the machines have an important role in the increasingly
popular client-server computing systems.
The market for mid-range machines is important to IBM as it struggles to
regain satisfactory profitability after three years of losses. The mainframe
computer business is no longer growing as customers shift to smaller,
cheaper computers of equivalent power.
IBM has reversed its declining market share in personal computers, but
margins there are narrow. However, the company has held a strong position in
the mid-range through its System/34 and System/38 computer families.
This is a potentially large market as customers trade up from PC systems or
trade down from mainframes. A mid-range machine is frequently the first
computer many medium-sized companies buy.
IBM's mid-range success was maintained by the launch of the first version of
the AS/400, three years ago, a computer derived from the System/38. It has
sold more than 250,000 systems.
However, the AS/400 retained a number of idiosyncratic features including a
special operating system and a closed structure which raised question marks
about its prospects.
Yesterday's launch showed that IBM has rethought the hardware and the
software of the AS/400. It will be able to run AS/400 programs, Unix (open
system) programs or OS/2 (PC) programs.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>International Business Machines Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
