<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / International Company News: Viacom looks at selling Madison
Square Garden
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Viacom, the US entertainment group, yesterday in effect put its Madison
Square Garden operations up for auction, signalling a disposal that analysts
expect to raise more than Dollars 1bn.
The company denied, though, that it was being forced into the sale by the
heavy debt load associated with its Dollars 10bn takeover of Paramount
Communications, the former owner of MSG.
Viacom said it had been approached by more than one potential buyer, and had
retained the investment bank Allen &amp; Co to evaluate offers.
Mr Sumner Redstone, the chairman of Viacom, said: 'While we have the option
of retaining this extraordinary asset and building on its many strengths, it
would be imprudent to ignore the many inquiries from possible buyers.'
Viacom would explore a sale of MSG 'as part of an orderly process for
determining how best to maximise shareholder value in the company.'
Mr Redstone's statement follows speculation that Viacom would be forced to
sell a number of assets. To help service debt resulting from the Paramount
takeover, the company has been counting on the completion of its planned
merger with Blockbuster Entertainment, the US video rental group.
Blockbuster itself has little debt and strong cashflow.
However, that transaction has looked in doubt as Viacom's B shares, the
currency for the deal, have tumbled in value in recent months - although the
shares rose Dollars 1 1/2 yesterday to close at Dollars 24 1/4 .
The MSG operations include the New York venue itself, two professional
sports franchises which play there - the Knicks basketball team and the
Rangers ice hockey team - and a sports cable television channel.
Viacom said that it had had 'expressions of interest from a number of
parties' interested in buying the operations, but did not say how far these
discussions had progressed or when it expected Allen to complete its
evaluation.
</TEXT>
