<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / International Company News: Eastman Kodak prepares for a new
image - The chairman decided the company should concentrate on its core
operations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The announcement by Mr George Fisher, chairman of Eastman Kodak, that the
group would sell its healthcare businesses delighted Wall Street for a
simple reason: many analysts and investors doubted that the new Kodak chief
had the guts to do it.
Ever since Mr Fisher joined the struggling photographic products group from
Motorola last December, Wall Street has waited for him to outline a strategy
for turning around Kodak, which has been criticised for its lacklustre
financial performance.
Most analysts were hoping Mr Fisher would choose to sell off Kodak's
non-core operations so it could concentrate on its photographic products and
imaging business. But few analysts were sure that he would be able to
engineer such a dramatic shift at a company renowned for its stodgy
corporate culture and resistance to change.
After all, Kodak had made five attempts in the past 10 years to restructure
its businesses and generate better earnings, and none had really worked. Why
would it be any different this time?
Yet, it was to be different because the new chairman realised soon after
joining Kodak that non-core operations were diverting much needed resources
away from the all-important imaging business. As he said yesterday: 'It
became increasingly apparent to me that we had this great set of businesses,
each of which had investment requirements that Kodak could not afford to
adequately cover.'
Consequently, Mr Fisher decided that if Kodak's imaging business was to
prosper in an increasingly competitive market, healthcare operations had to
go. Under the plan unveiled yesterday, the group will sell its
pharmaceutical and consumer health products unit Sterling Winthrop, its
personal care and household products business L&amp;F Products, and its Clinical
Diagnostics division. Between them, the three businesses generated almost a
quarter of Kodak's 1993 revenues of Dollars 16.4bn.
After the divestments, Kodak will be left with its imaging business and the
Health Sciences division. The latter, with its X-ray film and
electronics-based medical, cardiology, and dental diagnostic businesses, is
regarded as a vital part of Kodak's imaging strategy.
The ultimate aim of the restructuring is to allow Kodak to devote more funds
to developing its imaging business. Most of Kodak's photographic earnings
are derived from its traditional film products, which uses a chemical
process to create images. It is this business which is threatened by the
rapidly growing market for digital, electronic imaging.
Without the burden of supporting the healthcare operations, Kodak will be
able to spend more money on developing the electronic side of the imaging
business while simultaneously protecting its traditional imaging business
from competitors, and building sales of its photographic products.
The immediate impact of the divestments will be to improve dramatically the
group's financial condition. Kodak is labouring under Dollars 7bn of debt,
and the proceeds from the sale of the healthcare operations will go a long
way towards sharply reducing that figure. In turn, the reduction in debt
should lead to an improvement in the group's credit ratings.
Kodak does not expect the divestments to be dilutive. Mr Harry Kavetas,
chief financial officer, said: 'We would not expect any dilutive effect on
continuing earnings per share . . . because decreases in interest expense
that we will realise by applying the proceeds (of the sales) to debt
reductions should offset the loss of near-term profit contribution from the
sold units.'
Much depends, however, on what Kodak gets from the sale of its non-core
businesses. Although the group should have little trouble finding a buyer
for Sterling (the German group Bayer has already expressed an interest), few
expect it to recover the Dollars 5.1bn it spent acquiring the unit in 1988.
</TEXT>
