<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / UK Company News: T&amp;L arm takes majority of Orsan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Lafarge Coppee, the French building materials group, yesterday announced
that it is to sell its majority holding in Orsan, a food additives producer,
to Amylum of Belgium, a subsidiary of Tate and Lyle, for FFr414m.
The sale is part of Lafarge Coppee's strategy of withdrawing from the
bio-technology sector and effectively marks the end of this area of
diversification. It will also reduce Lafarge Coppe's borrowings by about
FFr1bn, following the transfer of debts to the Belgian company.
Orsan is involved in the manufacture of amino acids from starch and the
production of monosodium glutamate from molasses. It has an industrial
alliance with Ajinomoto of Japan, which holds 20 per cent of Orsan's shares.
Under the terms of the deal, Lafarge Coppee's Copabio division is to sell
its 61 per cent holding for FFr210 per share. This compares with a price of
FFr237 per share when Orsan was suspended on Monday.
</TEXT>
