<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / M0 increase eases fears over taxes: Indicators bolster
recovery hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A sharp rise in money supply last month yesterday provided the first
tentative statistical evidence that the spring tax increases have not
damaged the economic recovery.
The Bank of England reported that its provisional estimate of M0, the narrow
measure of money supply, increased by a seasonally adjusted 6.2 per cent in
the year to April, well up on market expectations of a 5.8 per cent increase
and a year-on-year rise of 5.6 per cent in March.
The news strengthened market expectations that Mr Kenneth Clarke, the
chancellor, and Mr Eddie George, the Bank of England governor, would decide
against cutting bank base rates from 5.25 per cent at their monthly monetary
meeting today.
A decision to change rates was already considered highly unlikely in view of
tomorrow's local elections, recent indicators of steady first-quarter
economic growth and rising yields for UK government bonds.
Yesterday's figures for M0, normally regarded as a good guide to retail
sales, provided the first statistical evidence that the tax increases have
not deterred UK consumers. 'The figures showed there is quite a lot of
momentum in consumer demand,' said Mr Adrian Cooper, UK economist at James
Capel, the stockbrokers.
M0, which consists of notes and coins in circulation and banks' operational
deposits, is regarded as a normally good guide to consumer spending trends.
Although increased taxes, including value added tax on domestic fuel, higher
employee National Insurance payments and reduced mortgage interest relief,
took effect at the beginning of last month, the growth of M0 in April alone
was an adjusted 1.9 per cent, the biggest monthly rise since February 1981.
The annual rate of M0 growth continues to be well above the government's
'monitoring range' of zero to 4 per cent which is meant to be consistent
with steady non-inflationary growth. On a seasonally adjusted annualised
basis, M0 rose by 13.1 per cent in the latest three months and 9.1 per cent
in the six months to April.
Notes and coins, the core component of M0 with the most relevance to
consumer trends, increased by a seasonally adjusted 6.5 per cent in the year
to April.
Bank officials said they regarded the sharp rise in M0 as a continuing
reaction to lower UK interest rates, which reduced the cost to individuals
of holding cash balances, and the steady growth of consumer demand. However,
they did not rule out technical factors because March, April and May are
traditionally difficult months for seasonal adjustment.
</TEXT>
