<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / CBI warns on rising wages: Factory pay 'up 2.7%'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Confederation of British Industry yesterday warned manufacturers to keep
pay awards under control as it published figures that showed settlements
edging up and productivity increases slowing.
According to the latest report from the CBI's pay databank, manufacturing
pay awards averaged 2.7 per cent during the first quarter of the year.
This was a slight increase on the 2.5 per cent average for pay awards in the
three months to February and it is ahead of the current inflation rate of
2.3 per cent.
Productivity improvements fell marginally, averaging 4.4 per cent
provisionally for the first quarter, compared with 4.6 per cent in the
second half of last year.
Mr Howard Davies, CBI director-general, warned that pay behaviour during the
coming months would determine whether or not manufacturing consolidated the
competitive gains made over the past couple of years.
He said: 'Other countries in Europe are now tackling their cost
competitiveness in a determined way. German labour costs are falling and pay
settlements are running well below the inflation rate.'
Pay settlements in service companies continued to drop over the first three
months of this year. Pay awards averaged 2.4 per cent for the first three
months of the year compared with 2.6 per cent for the last quarter of 1993.
The CBI figures show that in both manufacturing and service sectors the
spread of pay awards has widened, which it believes reflects 'the varied
picture of economic activity in different industries'.
One-in-six manufacturers and one-in-four service companies had imposed pay
freezes for periods of up to 12 months in the first quarter.
Since last August, 44.7 per cent of manufacturing settlements were between
0.1 per cent and 2.5 per cent, with a further 26.4 per cent making
settlements of between 2.5 per cent and 3.5 per cent and another 9.1 per
cent between 3.5 per cent and 4.5 per cent.
In services, 15.4 per cent of the private service settlements since last
August were freezes, while 34.8 per cent were between 0.1 and 2.5 per cent
and 28.5 per cent between 2.5 and 3.5 per cent.
Mr Alistair Hatchett of Incomes Data Services, the independent pay analysts,
said: 'Pay deals have been edging up since the start of the year reflecting
higher output and inflation. Firms appear to be settling faster because of
April's tax changes.'
The CBI databank annually covers about 1,200 settlements in manufacturing
and over 500 in services.
</TEXT>
