<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / Banks report mortgage surge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mortgage lending undertaken by leading British banks in March was more than
40 per cent higher than the equivalent figure in February, the British
Bankers' Association said yesterday.
Figures published by the association show gross lending at Pounds 1.55bn in
March, compared with Pounds 1.06bn in February, in a figure revised upwards
slightly from the originally published statistics.
There was also an increase in the number of new mortgages approved, which
reached 31,518, with a total value of Pounds 1.58bn. New mortgage approvals
are seen as an important indicator of prospects for the housing market, and
the total number for March is the highest since August last year.
Lord Inchyra, association director-general, said the figures for mortgage
approvals suggested that April's tax increases had had little immediate
impact on buyers' confidence.
While much of the increase in lending was attributed to seasonal factors, he
said that lending statistics provided 'welcome evidence of a recovery from
the normal seasonal weakness around the turn of the year'.
But the proportion of new mortgage approvals granted to first-time buyers
fell back to 46 per cent in March, from 50 per cent the month before.
The past year or so has seen intensifying competition for mortgage lending
between banks and building societies. In terms of market share, the
association said the increase in the value of new mortgages approved by
banks, at 38 per cent, was notably higher than the equivalent indicator for
building societies, where the rise in March amounted to 28 per cent.
House prices rose slightly in April, according to the Nationwide building
society index. This showed an increase of 0.2 per cent compared with March,
continuing a recent gently rising trend which takes the annual rate of
increase to 2.9 per cent.
</TEXT>
