<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / Heseltine denies big spending ambitions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Business Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, sought yesterday to
dampen speculation about his forthcoming white paper on competitiveness by
insisting that it would not propose big increases in government spending.
Mr Heseltine said the paper, to be published on May 16, would not contain
'gimmicks or short-term expedients' and would be consistent with the
evolutionary nature of the government's policies.
He said: 'The first priority of government in the promotion of UK
competitiveness is the proper management of the economy. Suggestions
therefore that we are about to indulge in an orgy of expenditure are not
only inaccurate but, much more to the point, would positively undermine our
own overriding priority.
'The white paper will not be the vehicle for announcing a range of lavish
new expenditure programmes. The government remains firmly committed to the
public expenditure ceilings announced by the chancellor in the Budget.'
Mr Heseltine said in a speech to the London International Financial Futures
and Options Exchange that the white paper had three main objectives: To set
out how the totality of the government's policies affected wealth-creating
businesses.
Assess the UK's competitive strengths and weaknesses.
Indicate 'how many of us in our own way are involved in the process of
helping our country to win'.
He also hinted that his proposals would contain a fresh broadside against
excessive regulation from Brussels, which he described as part of the
competitive challenge facing Britain. 'In Europe, we have hardly begun to
tackle the bureaucratic and restrictive nature of the procedures that are
characteristic of Community regulation,' he said.
He defended the government's record against criticisms in last week's report
on manufacturing competitiveness by the Commons trade and industry
committee. He said the report found much to applaud in the government's
policies towards industry.
</TEXT>
