<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / Patten taunted on NUS reversal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Patten, the education secretary, was taunted by Labour MPs yesterday
over his 'humiliating climbdown' in agreeing not to renew his attempt to
impose stricter controls over the National Union of Students, Ivor Owen
writes.
Moving the second reading of the education bill in the Commons, he formally
confirmed his acceptance of the watered-down provisions on student unions
introduced by the government to avoid an embarrassing defeat in the Lords.
But Mr Patten was insistent that an amendment requiring closer co-operation
with universities by schools involved in training graduate teachers -
inserted as a result of a government defeat in the Lords - should be
overturned.
The bill was given a second reading by a government majority of 55
(299-244).
</TEXT>
