<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / Treasury backs ID card
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Treasury has thrown its weight behind the government efficiency unit's
recommendation that identity cards should be issued for benefit claimants to
combat fraud in the Pounds 80bn social security budget.
The unit, headed by Sir Peter Levene, the prime minister's adviser on
efficiency, wants the government to launch a trial scheme in a small town.
The recommendation follows the presentation of a report by social security
officials arguing that cards could eliminate fraud running to hundreds of
million pounds.
Whitehall officials believe the Treasury's intervention may tip the balance
of power in favour of launching the pilot scheme, although the Department of
Social Security is fiercely resisting it.
The Home Office has also voiced 'concern' that the potential savings may not
outweigh political risks associated with the introduction of the cards.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, yesterday told the Commons that he had
'considerable sympathy' with those in favour of identity cards.
'There are practical difficulties, but we are examining them to see if they
can be overcome,' he said.
Mr Nicholas Budgen, a member of the Commons Treasury and civil service
committee, said many backbenchers strongly favoured introducing an identity
card system.
Both the DSS and Home Office are concerned that there is no overseas model
which has a proven track record of combating fraud.
But Mr Budgen said other countries were not necessarily suffering from the
same degree of fraud problems as the UK.
An identity card system would probably involve benefit claimants being
issued with cards which store encoded data on the shape of their hands. The
cards would be 'read' by electronic scans each time a benefit was collected.
Although the error rate on such scans is small, DSS and Home Office
ministers fear that a huge row would be caused if anyone was wrongly denied
benefit.
</TEXT>
