<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / Failures seem to hit steady rate: Business collapses reach
plateau
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of business failures appears to have steadied at about half the
level of 1992, says a survey published yesterday by Touche Ross, the
chartered accountants.
However, the number of receiverships and administrations, which totalled
about 2,500 in the last year, is running at well above pre-recession levels.
In 1989 there were 1,500 cases.
No clear pattern has yet emerged in the monthly receivership figures this
year. After two months when the number of receiverships increased, the
number of business failures dropped by 35 per cent in April to 171.
The average monthly number of failures in the first four months of this year
was 211, little lower than the average of 220 of the last 12 months.
Touche Ross said the recovery from recession continued to be slow and
cautious. Mr Ralph Preece, a partner at the firm, said: 'I remain of the
view that we are unlikely to see any dramatic fall in the number of business
failures unless and until there is a general resurgence in economic
confidence in the country at large.'
London and the south-east appeared to fare better in April at the expense of
the Midlands.
About 40 per cent of all failures were in the manufacturing sector, a
substantial increase over 1993 when the sector accounted for less than 30
per cent of failures. Part of this increase was accounted for by the
collapse of the Bimec Industries Group in the West Midlands.
Failures in the building and construction sector fell to 16 per cent of all
failures, compared with 20 per cent in 1993. Touche Ross based its figures
on the receivership and administration appointments advertised in the London
and Edinburgh Gazettes. The figures, which exclude liquidations, indicate
the pressures on larger companies although they are a fraction of the total
number of business failures.
</TEXT>
