<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / Boarding schools seek extra funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Boarding schools, which suffered a 5.2 per cent drop in boarding pupil
numbers last year, are discussing possible extra state funds with education
ministers.
Mr Ian Small, chairman of the Boarding Schools Association, which represents
both independent and state boarding schools, and headmaster of Bootham
School in York, said: 'At the moment there are a lot of financial
constraints on parents.
'There are a number of state boarding schools which have actually increased
their numbers recently, and there are various ways in which boarding schools
might be made more flexible.'
He suggested that the government could contribute towards independent
schools' salary bills, using a model used in Europe, or it could expand the
assisted places scheme, which funds children from low-income families to
attend independent schools.
Mr Paul High, headmaster of the Prior's Court preparatory school in
Berkshire, said the assisted places scheme could be extended to pupils aged
more than seven or nine. At present, the funding is only available from the
age of 11, effectively excluding most preparatory schools. He said: 'If the
government is acting to support education, why only start at 11? If they
have a commitment why shouldn't we be able to offer the facilities we have
to more parents?'
Mr Small expressed reservations about the scheme, unveiled at the end of
last year, to allow independent schools to 'opt in' to the state sector and
become grant-maintained schools. A number of schools were considering the
move, he said, but were not prepared to go further until government
regulations on eliminating surplus places had been clarified.
</TEXT>
