<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / Names promised new deal: Lloyd's reform package aims to
strengthen rights of members
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lloyd's of London yesterday paved the way for a further transformation of
its capital base by providing for the possible operation of syndicates
backed by a single corporate investor, effectively insurance companies, at
the market.
It has proposed a package of reforms which would strengthen the rights of
individual Names, whose assets support the market.
It has also suggested ways in which those Names continuing to trade may be
able to obtain cash or shares in new corporate syndicates or other vehicles
in exchange for their existing syndicate participations.
'The measures and proposals set out in this report maintain a programme of
radical reform which we initiated a year ago,' said Mr David Rowland,
Lloyd's chairman. Lloyd's introduced Pounds 800m in new corporate capital
last year.
Mr Peter Middleton, chief executive, said Lloyd's would consult on its
proposals for 'transferring or realising value' for syndicate
participations. 'The changes will have a profound and positive impact on the
future of Lloyd's,' he said.
The market does not intend to change rules limiting the amount of capital
corporate investors can supply to syndicates. Single corporate Names can
supply no more than 25 per cent of a syndicate's capacity - the amount of
premiums it can accept - while overall, syndicates can obtain no more than
50 per cent of their capacity from corporate Names.
However, Mr Rowland said Lloyd's Council, the body that governs the market,
could make exceptions and conceded that 'it is inevitable that at some point
in the future we will revisit these regulations'.
In its report Lloyd's said single corporate members, if introduced, would be
able to adopt annual accounting - in contrast to the three-year system of
existing syndicates.
Mr Robert Hiscox, Lloyd's deputy chairman and a keen supporter of the idea,
said the new type of syndicate would allow managers 'complete stability of
capital, and to retain earnings and plan long-term'.
The establishment of single corporate members is one of three possible ways
in which Names may be able to realise value from their participations.
Lloyd's will also examine the feasibility of a market where participations
can be traded, as well as the possibility that Names might sell a range of
syndicate participations to an investor, in exchange for shares, other
securities or cash.
The plan makes no provision for Names unable to trade because of past
losses, or for those who have already resigned or left the market.
The Association of Lloyd's Members, which represents about 9,000 Names,
welcomed the proposals and said that moves to introduce pre-emption rights
and syndicate voting rights amounted to an 'important recognition of the
inherent rights of Names'.
</TEXT>
