<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / Syndicates to offer added value: Richard Lapper reports on
the details of the market's radical plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'A mountain of complications' to lead Lloyd's to the 'greenfields of
simplicity' was how Mr David Rowland, chairman of Lloyd's, described
yesterday's package of reforms at the insurance market.
The reforms, outlined in a 64-page document entitled Value at Lloyd's, are
designed to allow Names to obtain value from their long-term interests in
syndicates - the one-year annual joint ventures that conduct insurance
business.
Names currently share only in the annual profits or losses of their
syndicates but Mr Rowland said he wanted them to be able to 'realise any
capital value or goodwill of the syndicate business'.
The document starts by giving the Names who continue to underwrite next year
pre-emption rights over the syndicates they support. These rights - similar
to those typically available to a shareholder in a listed company - would
allow Names to maintain their existing shares in syndicates from year to
year or increase them in proportion to the syndicate's increase in capacity
(the amount of business it can underwrite).
Names will also be given voting rights, allowing them to have more influence
in any decision by their agent to increase capacity.
Names are also to be given the right to transfer a participation for future
years of account to another member, through the introduction of
'assignment', a reform described as a 'fundamental building block' for any
system of value.
The Lloyd's agency agreement - which governs the current relationship
between a Name and his agent - is to be modified this year with the changes
also coming into effect in 1995.
On the basis of these initial steps, Lloyd's will then examine ways in which
a market can be set up, allowing Names to 'realise' the value of their
syndicate participations.
Here - for the moment at least - Lloyd's has been less proscriptive. Three
basic routes forward are outlined but each of them will require further
work.
'It is better to let outside brains work on how we should do it best,'
explains Mr Robert Hiscox, the deputy chairman who headed the team which
prepared yesterday's report.
Separately, Lloyd's also announced measures designed to secure a more
efficient allocation of capital. A system of risk-based capital, in which
the funds required by investors to back insurance business will vary
according to the risks underwritten and exposures, is to be introduced.
Lloyd's is also committed to intervening to prevent excessive increases in
the capacity of the market. A new system will be introduced for reviewing
significant increases proposed by managing agents, who administer
syndicates.
All this should mean Lloyd's will be better equipped to prevent another
period of disastrous losses as in the 1980s, when excessive capacity led
many underwriters to accept risks for too little premiums. But that will be
little comfort for the thousands of Names already ruined.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
                    How Names might cash in
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Creation of a market administered by Lloyd's where Names could buy and
sell their participations in syndicates while maintaining their
existing status. The report reviews a number of ways that this might be
achieved. It concludes that a one-off auction-based tender system, in
which all sellers of a particular syndicate receive the same price, is
the most likely option in the short term.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Corporate pooling arrangements: members would 'assign' all their
syndicate participations to a corporate member in exchange for shares,
other securities or cash.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Corporate syndicates: in which members of one syndicate would 'assign'
future participations to a corporate member, again in exchange for
shares, other securities or cash.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
